window.__QUIZ_DATA__=[{"id":"theory>Physics Practical>2001>1>a","subject":"Physics Practical","year":"2001","type":"Practical","sub_label":"a","group":"","topic":"EQUILIBRIUM OF FORCES : CONDITIONS FOR EQUILIBRIUM OF RIGID BODIES UNDER THE ACTION OF PARALLEL AND NON-PARALLEL FORCES","question":"(i) Fix the 100 g mass, marked P, at B, the 80 cm mark of the uniform metre rule, using an adhesive.  (ii) Suspend another 100 g mass marked Q at A, a distance V = 10.0 cm from the 0 cm mark of the metre rule.  (iii) Balance the whole arrangement horizontally on a knife edge as shown in the diagram above.  (iv) Measure and record the distance, U, of K from the 0 cm mark of the metre rule.  (v) Repeat the procedure for five other values of V = 15.0, 20.0, 25.0, 30.0 and 35.0 cm.  (vi) In each case, measure and record the corresponding values U. Tabulate your readings.  (vii) Plot a graph of U on the vertical axis against V on the horizontal axis.  (viii) Determine the:  1. slope, s, of the graph  2. intercept, c, on the vertical axis.  (ix) Evaluate:  1. K1 = (1\u22122ss\\frac{1-2s}{s}s1\u22122s\u200b)100  2. K2 = 2cs\\frac{2c}{s}s2c\u200b - 160  (x) State two precautions taken to ensure accurate results.","images":["data:image/jpeg;base64,","data:image/png;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"S/NV(cm)U(cm)110.0047.00215.0048.30320.0049.40425.0051.20530.0052.50635.0054.00        s = y2\u2212y1x2\u2212x1\\frac{y_{2}-y_{1}}{x_{2}-x_{1}}x2\u200b\u2212x1\u200by2\u200b\u2212y1\u200b\u200b = 54\u22124735\u221210\\frac{54-47}{35-10}35\u22121054\u221247\u200b = 725\\frac{7}{25}257\u200b = 0.28    c = 44 cm    K1 = (1\u22122ss\\frac{1-2s}{s}s1\u22122s\u200b)100 = (1\u22122\u00d70.280.28\\frac{1-2\u00d70.28}{0.28}0.281\u22122\u00d70.28\u200b)100 = (1\u22120.560.28\\frac{1-0.56}{0.28}0.281\u22120.56\u200b)100 = (0.440.28\\frac{0.44}{0.28}0.280.44\u200b)100 = 157.14    K2 = 2cs\\frac{2c}{s}s2c\u200b - 160 = 2\u00d7440.28\\frac{2\u00d744}{0.28}0.282\u00d744\u200b - 160 = 880.28\\frac{88}{0.28}0.2888\u200b - 160 = 154.29    Precautions:  1. I avoided parallax error by positioning my eyes directly in line with the scale of the metre rule, ensuring accurate readings.    2. I ensured that the mass was fully suspended and did not rest on the table, allowing it to balance solely on the knife edge to avoid interference with the experimental results.    3. I ensured the knife edge was placed precisely to maintain a stable balance and prevent the mass from slipping during the experiment.    4. I made sure that all apparatus were stable and properly positioned to avoid external disturbances during the measurements.","marks":"21","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"theory>Physics Practical>2001>1>b>i","subject":"Physics Practical","year":"2001","type":"Practical","sub_label":"i","group":"","topic":"EQUILIBRIUM OF FORCES : CONDITIONS FOR EQUILIBRIUM OF RIGID BODIES UNDER THE ACTION OF PARALLEL AND NON-PARALLEL FORCES","question":"State two conditions under which a rigid body at rest remains in equilibrium when acted upon by three non-parallel coplanar forces.","images":["data:image/jpeg;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"1. The vector sum of the forces must be zero: The forces must balance each other so that no net force acts on the body, ensuring translational equilibrium.    2. The forces must be concurrent: The three forces must meet at a common point to prevent any rotational imbalances.    3. The sum of the moments of the forces about any point must be zero: This ensures there is no net torque acting on the body, maintaining rotational equilibrium.","marks":"2","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"theory>Physics Practical>2001>1>b>ii","subject":"Physics Practical","year":"2001","type":"Practical","sub_label":"ii","group":"CLOSENESS","topic":"EQUILIBRIUM OF FORCES : CENTRE OF GRAVITY AND STABILITY","question":"Explain how the position of the centre of gravity of a body affects the equilibrium of the body.","images":["data:image/jpeg;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"The position of the center of gravity (CG) significantly affects a body's equilibrium. A lower CG increases stability, making it harder for the body to topple, while a higher CG makes it more prone to tipping. A body remains in equilibrium as long as its CG stays within its base of support; if the CG moves outside this base, the body loses balance and may topple.    Additionally, the CG determines the type of equilibrium. A low CG results in stable equilibrium, where the body returns to its original position after being slightly displaced. A high CG leads to unstable equilibrium, where displacement causes the body to move further away from its initial position. Neutral equilibrium occurs when the CG remains at the same height during displacement, so the body neither returns to nor moves further from its original position.","marks":"2","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"theory>Physics Practical>2001>2>a","subject":"Physics Practical","year":"2001","type":"Practical","sub_label":"a","group":"CLOSENESS","topic":"LIGHT WAVES : REFRACTION OF LIGHT AT CURVED SURFACES","question":"Using the diagram beside as a guide, carry out the following instructions  (i) Place the pin, O, horizontally inside the cylinder provided. Pour some water on the pin in the cylinder such that the length of the water column,  l  = SO = 10.0 cm, where S represents the water meniscus.  (ii) Insert another pin, P, in the cork held by the boss of the retort stand.  (iii) Adjust the position of P vertically upward or downward until it coincides with the image I of O formed by refraction at S.  (iv) Read and record the distance h = PO  (v) Repeat the procedure for four other values of  l  = 15, 20, 25 and 30 cm.  (vi) In each case, measure and record the corresponding value of h. Tabulate your readings.  (vii) Plot a graph of h on the vertical axis against  l  on the horizontal axis.  (viii) Determine the slope, s, of the graph.","images":["data:image/jpeg;base64,","data:image/png;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"S/N l (cm)h(cm)110.007.50215.0011.25320.0015.00425.0018.75530.0022.50        s = y2\u2212y1x2\u2212x1\\frac{y_{2}-y_{1}}{x_{2}-x_{1}}x2\u200b\u2212x1\u200by2\u200b\u2212y1\u200b\u200b = 22.5\u22127.530\u221210\\frac{22.5-7.5}{30-10}30\u22121022.5\u22127.5\u200b = 1520\\frac{15}{20}2015\u200b = 0.75    K1 = 1 - s = 1 - 0.75 = 0.25    K2 = 1K1\\frac{1}{K_{1}}K1\u200b1\u200b = 10.25\\frac{1}{0.25}0.251\u200b = 4    Precautions:  1. I avoided parallax error by ensuring my eye was level with the surface of the water when taking readings, specifically reading the lower meniscus of the water in the measuring cylinder.    2. I filled the measuring cylinder slowly to prevent splashing that could disturb the pin or affect the water level.    3. I ensured the pin remained fixed at the bottom of the cylinder and did not float or shift during the experiment.    4. I placed the measuring cylinder on a flat, stable surface to keep it vertical and avoid any distortion in my displacement measurement.    5. I checked for and eliminated any air bubbles trapped around the pin or in the water, as these could interfere with my readings.    6. I used clean equipment to ensure that the measuring cylinder and pin were free from debris, which might affect my measurements.    7. I took measurements only after the water had settled completely to avoid errors caused by movement in the water.","marks":"21","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"theory>Physics Practical>2001>2>b>i","subject":"Physics Practical","year":"2001","type":"Practical","sub_label":"i","group":"","topic":"LIGHT WAVES : REFRACTION OF LIGHT AT PLANE SURFACES","question":"Explain total internal reflection of light.","images":["data:image/jpeg;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"Total internal reflection occurs when a light ray traveling from a denser medium to a less dense medium strikes the boundary at an angle greater than the critical angle, resulting in the light being completely reflected back into the denser medium instead of refracting, and this phenomenon is crucial for applications such as fiber optics and optical devices like prisms.","marks":"2","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"theory>Physics Practical>2001>2>b>ii","subject":"Physics Practical","year":"2001","type":"Practical","sub_label":"ii","group":"FINAL","topic":"LIGHT WAVES : REFRACTION OF LIGHT AT PLANE SURFACES","question":"A rectangular glass prism of thickness 6 cm and refractive index 1.5 is placed on the page of a book. The prints on the book are viewed vertically downwards from above. Determine the apparent upward displacement of the prints.    (Provide your answer with unit e.g 123 N)","images":["data:image/jpeg;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"n = 1.5; real depth = 6 cm    n=real depthapparent depth  1.5 = 6A\\frac{6}{A}A6\u200b    1.5A = 6    A = 61.5\\frac{6}{1.5}1.56\u200b = 4 cm    apparent upward displacement of the prints = real depth - apparent depth    apparent upward displacement of the prints =  6 cm - 4 cm    \u2234 apparent upward displacement of the prints =  2 cm","marks":"2","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"theory>Physics Practical>2001>3>a","subject":"Physics Practical","year":"2001","type":"Practical","sub_label":"a","group":"CLOSENESS","topic":"ELECTRIC FIELD : RESISTIVITY AND CONDUCTIVITY","question":"You are provided with two wires marked P and Q, a resistor RS = 1 \u03a9 and other necessary apparatus.  (i) Connect RS in the left hand gap of the metre bridge, a length L = 100 cm of wire P in the right hand gap and the other apparatus as shown in the diagram above.  (ii) Determine the balance point, B, on the bridge wire AC  (iii) Measure and record AB =  l S and BC =  l P.  (iv) Evaluate R1 = (lPlS\\frac{l_{P}}{l_{S}}lS\u200blP\u200b\u200b)RS.  (v) Repeat the procedure for four other values of L = 90, 80, 70 and 60 cm. In each case, obtain and record the values of  l S and  l P and evaluate R1 = (lPlS\\frac{l_{P}}{l_{S}}lS\u200blP\u200b\u200b)RS.  (vi) Repeat the experiment with the second wire, Q. Obtain values of  l S and  l Q for equal lengths of wire as used in wire P.  (vii) Evaluate R2 = (lQlS\\frac{l_{Q}}{l_{S}}lS\u200blQ\u200b\u200b)RS in each case. Tabulate your readings.  (viii) Plot a graph of R2 on the vertical axis against R1 on the horizontal axis.  (ix) Determine the slope, s, of the graph.  (x) Evaluate k = &radic;s&nbsp;  (xi) State two precautions taken to ensure accurate results.","images":["data:image/jpeg;base64,","data:image/png;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"S/NL(cm) l S(cm) l P(cm)R1(\u03a9) l S1(cm) l Q(cm)R2(\u03a9)11005.3094.7017.9021.6078.403.602906.5093.5014.4022.1077.903.503807.0093.0013.3023.4076.603.304708.5091.5010.8024.3075.703.105609.5090.509.5025.3074.702.95    Where R1 = (lPlS\\frac{l_{P}}{l_{S}}lS\u200blP\u200b\u200b)RS and R2 = (lQlS\\frac{l_{Q}}{l_{S}}lS\u200blQ\u200b\u200b)RS        s = y2\u2212y1x2\u2212x1\\frac{y_{2}-y_{1}}{x_{2}-x_{1}}x2\u200b\u2212x1\u200by2\u200b\u2212y1\u200b\u200b = 3.6\u2212317\u22129.5\\frac{3.6-3}{17-9.5}17\u22129.53.6\u22123\u200b = 225\\frac{2}{25}252\u200b = 0.08    k = &radic;s&nbsp; = &radic;0.08&nbsp; = 0.28    Precautions:  1. I ensured that the key was opened when readings were not being taken  2. I avoided error due to parallax when reading the metre rule","marks":"21","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"theory>Physics Practical>2001>3>b>i","subject":"Physics Practical","year":"2001","type":"Practical","sub_label":"i","group":"","topic":"ELECTRIC FIELD : RESISTIVITY AND CONDUCTIVITY","question":"Define  resistivity  of the material of a wire.","images":["data:image/jpeg;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"Resistivity of the material of a wire is a measure of how strongly the material opposes the flow of electric current. It is defined as the resistance of a unit length of the wire with a unit cross-sectional area. Mathematically, resistivity (\u03c1) is given by:  \u03c1 = R &#215; AL\\frac{A}{L}LA\u200b  where:  R is the resistance of the wire,  A is the cross-sectional area,  L is the length of the wire.","marks":"2","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"theory>Physics Practical>2001>3>b>ii","subject":"Physics Practical","year":"2001","type":"Practical","sub_label":"ii","group":"FINAL","topic":"ELECTRIC FIELD : CURRENT ELECTRICITY","question":"A galvanometer with a full-scale-deflection of 1.5 \u00d7 10-3 A, has a resistance of 50 \u03a9. Determine the resistance required to convert it into a voltmeter, reading up to 1.5 V.    (Please provide your answer without the unit)","images":["data:image/jpeg;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"V = Vg + VR = IRg + IR    V = I(Rg + R)    Rg + R = VI\\frac{V}{I}IV\u200b    R = VI\\frac{V}{I}IV\u200b - Rg    R = 1.51.5\u00d710\u22123\\frac{1.5}{1.5\u00d710^{-3}}1.5\u00d710\u221231.5\u200b - 50    R = 1000 - 50    \u2234 R = 950 \u03a9","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"}];